Another way of considering expected investor returns is to take the reciprocal of the buyer's expected rate of return, or capitalization rate, which then becomes a selling multiple. For example, an 18.0% weighted average cost of capital corresponds to an acquisition multiple of 5.6 (1/.18). This is a shorthand way of considering this issue, as the conversion does not incorporate long-term growth. In general terms, this prospective buyer could pay 5.6 times the benefit stream for an acquisition candidate and still meets its expectation. In this case, the buyer is betting that the benefit stream will continue for a minimum of 5.6 years. Increases in the benefit stream over the six years would increase the buyer's overall return.

